The rates of spreading and direction of motion along a specific mid-ocean ridge are relatively consistent. The relative velocity between the European and North American plates at (45.00, 330.00) is 23.63 mm/year with azimuth N276.8E, while the relative velocity along the same ridges at (20.00, 315.00) is 24.64 mm/year with azimuth N269.6E. The relative velocity between the African and South American plates at (-10.00, 345.00) is 34.76 mm/year with azimuth N258.6E, and is 34.88 mm/year with azimuth N258.6E at \cf4 \cb1 (-40.00, 345.00). The relative velocity between the North American and Pacific plates at (25.00, 250.00) is 49.12 mm/year with azimuth N308.1E and 51.01 mm/year with azimuth N300.6E at (20.00, 255.00). The relative velocity between the Nazca and Pacific plates at (-5.00, 255.00) is 139.39 mm/year with azimuth N279.5E and 154.96 mm/year with azimuth N284.1E at (-20.00, 245.00). The relative velocity between the Antarctic and Pacific plates at (-60.00, 210.00) is 72.96 mm/year with azimuth N303.3E and 82.23 mm/year with azimuth N294.5E at (-55.00, 225.00). The relative velocity between the Arabian and African plates at (18.00, 40.00) is 12.86 mm/year with azimuth N205.0E and 8.08 mm/year with azimuth N177.2E at (25.00, 35.00). The greatest variation in the rate of motion along the observed mid-ocean ridge\'92s was roughly 15 mm/year, between two points along the ridge formed by the Nazca and Pacific plates. The largest variation in the the direction of motion was roughly 28 degrees, between two points along the mid-ocean ridge formed by the Arabian and African plates. Other than those two exceptions  the observed values were fairly consistent along each mid-ocean ridge.\
\
