The greatest variation in the rate of motion along the observed mid-ocean ridge\'92s was roughly 15 mm/year, between two points along the ridge formed by the Nazca and Pacific plates. As stated in the previous answer, the values for rates of spreading, as well as the direction of movement, are fairly consistent along specific mid-ocean ridges, with the exception of minor variations (up to 15mm/year, and 30 degrees of direction). The average variations for these values however, are within 5 mm/year and degrees of direction. The rate of spreading varies greatly depending upon which region of the pacific plate is being bordered. The mid-ocean ridge along the Nazca and Pacific plates is spreading much more rapidly (145 mm/year average) than the ridge formed along the Antarctic and Pacific plates (77 mm/year average), and the ridge formed along the North American and Pacific pates (50mm/year average).\
