\cf2 \cb3 Rank order (1 to 6 from slowest to fastest) the average spreading rates of the six different mid-ocean ridges (i.e. N Atlantic, S Atlantic, NE Pacific, E. Pacific, S. Pacific & Red Sea). Among the six ridges the NE Pacific - Gulf of California and the Red Sea are the youngest spreading centers. Do the data for these mid-ocean ridges - in comparison with the other more established ridges - aid understanding of how the rates of spreading may vary over the lifetime of an ocean basin?\cf4 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\sa200
\cf4 3.)\
The average rates of spreading along the observed mid-ocean ridges are, in order from slowest to fastest, are as follows. The ridge between the Arabian and African plates spreads at approximately 10.8 mm/year, the ridge between the European and North American plates spreads at approximately 24.13 mm/year, the ridge between the African and South American plates spreads at approximately 34.8 mm/year, the ridge between the North American and Pacific plates spreads at approximately 50 mm/year, the ridge between the Pacific and Antarctic plates spreads at approximately 77.5 mm/year, and the ridge between the Nazca and Pacific plates spreads at approximately 146.9 mm/year. The data for the younger spreading ridges, when compared to the older spreading ridges, suggests that the rate of spreading for the mid ocean ridges may be influenced by the age of the mid-ocean ridge itself. The younger the spreading center, the faster the rate of spreading is, suggesting that as time passes, spreading plates lose energy, and subsequently, speed as they move farther from the spreading center. \
